title: Finding decompress algorithm for unknown compression
content:
I have a raw data of what seems to be a compressed PNG file and I need to find the decompress algorithm for unknown compression.
You can see the file here.
I think they are using some kind of LZRW 1 with some strange dictionary build routine.

I succeed to de-compress the IHeader of the file correctly (I verified it with CRC).
This the comparing between them:

This is the algorithm it worked with:

There is a 1 byte flag every each 8 bytes.
If the flag is > 0 I am checking its bits.
For example:
08 (0000 1000) 00 00 02 58 (00 83) 5A 08 06

The flag is 08 => 0000 1000
So it need to go 5 step forward after the flag => 00 83 ....

The dictionary looks to be built by 2 bytes, for example: 00 83
In binary:
0000 0000 1000 0011

The first 4 bits from the right are might be the length and the rest (12 bits) are probably the absolute offset.
offset length
(0000 0000 1000) (0011)

I looked to the next flags after the first chunk dictionary (0x0 0x83) and saw a new dictionaries (0x9 0x84) but it doesn't work well:

This is the "best" result I received with my algorithm:

My algorithm pseudo-code: 

data = readFile(filePath)
i = 0
while i < len(data):
    controlbits = data[i] // controlbits is 8 bites
    i += 1
    for bit in controlbits:
        if bit == 0:
            output += data[i]
            i += 1
        else: // bit is 1
            // Example: data[i] = 0x0, data[i+1] = 0x83
            // data[i] = 0000 0000
            // data[i+1] = 1000 0011
            // dict = 0000 0000 1000 0011
            dict = data[i] << 8
            dict |=  data[i+1]


            offset = dict[0:12]
            len = dict[12:16]
            output += output[offset: offset+len]
            i += 2

comments.text: Pretty sure you've thought of this but do you have other examples of the compression? Maybe a plain text, XML files or something that isn't compressed to start with. It'd make it easier to guess how the dictionary is built then.

Unfortunately not because it was a part of a CTF and the challenge is to figure out the decompression algorithm without knowing the compression. You need to figure it out just by looking on the compressed image. The PNG has a standard header so it should be the clue, because I already showed how I figure out the origin header but we need to do it also on the data.
